om their homes, this book explores the possibility of forgiveness. The contributors to this book draw upon the insights of history, political science, philosophy, and psychology to examine the trauma left in the wake of such actions, using, as examples, numerous case studies from the Holocaust, Russia, Cambodia, Guatemala, South Africa, and even Canada. They consider the fundamental psychological and philosophical issues that have to be confronted, offer insights about measures that can be taken to facilitate healing, and summarize what has been learned from previous struggles. Dilemmas of Reconciliation is a pioneering effort that explores the extraordinary challenges that must be faced in the aftermath of genocide or barbarous civil wars. How these challenges of reconciliation are faced and resolved will affect not only the victims’ ability to go on with their lives but will impact regional stability and, ultimately, world peace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relationsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMorale politique. 0aPolitical ethics. 0aReconciliation. 0aRelations internationalesxAspect moral. 0aRéconciliation. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy: Ethics. 4aPolitical Science. 4aPolitical Science: International Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aChandler, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrocker, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpp, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForget, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstone, Justice Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1